    "question": "What is the CAP theorem?",
    "answer": "The CAP theorem (Brewer's theorem) says that any distributed data store can guarantee at most two of the following three properties at the same time:\n\n- **Consistency (C)** — every read returns the most recently written value, or an error. All nodes see the same data simultaneously.\n- **Availability (A)** — every request receives a non-error response, without any guarantee that it contains the latest data.\n- **Partition tolerance (P)** — the system keeps operating even when the network drops or delays arbitrary messages between nodes.\n\nBecause real networks can always partition, a distributed system effectively has to pick between **CP** and **AP** whenever a partition happens. Some examples:\n\n- **CP systems**: HBase, MongoDB (with majority writes), ZooKeeper, etcd — they may refuse requests to preserve consistency.\n- **AP systems**: Cassandra, DynamoDB, CouchDB, Riak — they keep serving reads/writes and reconcile later via mechanisms like read repair or vector clocks.\n- A single-node RDBMS is often described as \"CA\", but that's only meaningful when no partition is possible (i.e. it's not actually distributed).\n\nIn practice CAP is a coarse model. The PACELC extension adds: **else** (when there is no partition), trade off between **L**atency and **C**onsistency — which better matches real systems."
