    "answer": "**Vertical scaling (scale up)** means making a single machine more powerful — more CPU, RAM, faster disks, or moving to a bigger instance type. No code changes are needed, but you eventually hit a hardware ceiling and a single point of failure.\n\n**Horizontal scaling (scale out)** means adding more machines and distributing load across them with a load balancer. There is effectively no ceiling, but the application has to be designed for it: stateless services, shared session storage, distributed caches, and a sharded or replicated data tier.\n\n| Aspect | Horizontal scaling | Vertical scaling |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| How you grow | Add more machines | Upgrade the existing machine |\n| Upper limit | Practically unlimited | Hardware ceiling of one box |\n| Failure resilience | High — traffic reroutes when a node fails | Low — the single node is a SPOF |\n| Load balancing | Required | Not required |\n| Inter-node communication | Network-bound (slower) | In-process (fast) |\n| Data consistency | Harder (replication, sharding) | Easy (single node) |\n| Cost curve | Linear or sub-linear with commodity hardware | Steep — high-end hardware gets disproportionately expensive |\n| Typical examples | Stateless web tier behind an ELB, Cassandra, Kafka | A single Postgres primary on a bigger instance |\n\nMost modern cloud architectures combine the two: vertically scale individual nodes up to a sweet spot, then horizontally scale by adding more of them."
