    "number": 3,
    "question": "What is load balancing and why is it important?",
    "answer": "A **load balancer** sits in front of a pool of backend servers and distributes incoming requests across them. It is one of the most important building blocks of any scalable system.\n\nCommon distribution algorithms:\n\n- **Round-robin** — rotate through servers in order.\n- **Least connections** — send to the server with the fewest active connections.\n- **Least response time** — send to the fastest-responding server.\n- **Weighted** variants of the above when nodes differ in capacity.\n- **Consistent hashing** — send requests with the same key (e.g. user ID) to the same backend, minimising cache churn when nodes are added or removed.\n\nWhy it matters:\n\n- **Prevents overload** of any single server, so latency stays predictable.\n- **Eliminates single points of failure** — when a server goes down, health checks pull it out of the pool and traffic reroutes automatically.\n- **Enables zero-downtime deploys** by draining one server at a time.\n- **Terminates TLS** at the edge so backends don't each need certificates.\n- **Enables horizontal scaling** — adding capacity is just registering new instances.\n\nLoad balancers operate at different layers:\n\n- **L4 (transport)** — routes by IP/port without inspecting payloads (e.g. AWS NLB, HAProxy in TCP mode). Very fast.\n- **L7 (application)** — understands HTTP, so it can route by path, header, cookie, or hostname (e.g. AWS ALB, NGINX, Envoy, Traefik). Required for path-based routing, sticky sessions, and most API gateways.\n\nFor high availability, the load balancer itself is usually deployed in an active-passive or active-active pair behind a virtual IP, or as a managed cloud service."
