    "number": 4,
    "question": "What do latency, throughput, and availability mean?",
    "answer": "These are the three headline performance and reliability metrics for any system.\n\n- **Latency** — the time taken to handle a single request, end to end. Usually reported as a distribution (p50, p95, p99) rather than an average, because tail latency drives user experience. Measured in milliseconds (or microseconds for very fast systems).\n- **Throughput** — how much work the system can handle per unit time. Measured in requests per second, transactions per second, bits per second, or messages per second depending on the workload.\n- **Availability** — the fraction of time the system is up and serving correct responses. Calculated as `uptime / (uptime + downtime)` and usually expressed in \"nines\":\n\n| Availability | Downtime per year |\n| --- | --- |\n| 99% (two nines) | ~3.65 days |\n| 99.9% (three nines) | ~8.77 hours |\n| 99.99% (four nines) | ~52.6 minutes |\n| 99.999% (five nines) | ~5.26 minutes |\n\nA few important caveats:\n\n- **Latency and throughput are not the same thing.** A pipeline can have high latency per item but high throughput if it pipelines many items in parallel (Little's Law: `concurrency = throughput × latency`).\n- **Availability stacks multiplicatively** across dependencies. A service that calls three 99.9% dependencies serially has at best ~99.7% availability.\n- **SLO vs SLA** — an SLO is your internal target (e.g. \"p99 < 200ms\"), an SLA is the contractual promise to customers, usually looser than the SLO with financial penalties attached."
