    "number": 5,
    "question": "What is sharding?",
    "answer": "**Sharding** is horizontally partitioning a dataset across multiple databases (shards), so each shard holds only a subset of the data. It's how you scale a database past what one machine can hold or serve.\n\nEach shard is a fully independent database with its own storage and CPU. A shard key (e.g. `user_id`) determines which shard a given row lives on.\n\nCommon sharding strategies:\n\n- **Range-based** — split by ranges of the key (`user_id 1-1M` on shard A, `1M-2M` on shard B). Simple range scans, but hot shards if traffic skews.\n- **Hash-based** — hash the key and mod by shard count. Even distribution, but range queries hit every shard.\n- **Consistent hashing** — hash both keys and nodes onto a ring; only a fraction of keys move when a shard is added or removed.\n- **Directory-based** — a lookup service maps each key to a shard. Maximum flexibility, but the directory becomes a SPOF that needs its own HA story.\n\nBenefits: higher throughput, more storage, smaller per-shard indexes, parallel queries.\n\nCosts and pitfalls:\n\n- **Cross-shard joins and transactions** are hard — usually you denormalise or use a saga pattern.\n- **Re-sharding** (splitting a hot shard) is operationally painful unless you used consistent hashing from day one.\n- **Hot spots** — a poorly chosen shard key (e.g. timestamp on a write-heavy workload) sends all traffic to one shard.\n- **Operational overhead** — backups, schema migrations, and monitoring all get more complex."
