    "number": 6,
    "question": "How is a NoSQL database different from a SQL database?",
    "answer": "**SQL (relational)** databases store structured data in tables with fixed schemas and enforce relationships and ACID transactions. **NoSQL** is an umbrella term for non-relational stores that trade some of those guarantees for scalability, flexibility, or different data models.\n\n| Aspect | SQL | NoSQL |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Data model | Tables with rows and columns | Document, key-value, wide-column, graph |\n| Schema | Strict, defined upfront | Flexible / schema-on-read |\n| Query language | Standardised SQL | Varies by store (MongoDB query, CQL, Gremlin, etc.) |\n| Transactions | Full ACID | Often BASE (eventual consistency); some support ACID within a partition |\n| Scaling | Primarily vertical; horizontal via sharding/read replicas | Designed for horizontal scaling out of the box |\n| Joins | First-class | Limited or absent; denormalise instead |\n| Consistency | Strong by default | Tunable, often eventual |\n| Best for | Complex relationships, transactions, reporting | High write throughput, large unstructured data, simple access patterns |\n| Examples | PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQL Server, Oracle | MongoDB, Cassandra, DynamoDB, Redis, Neo4j |\n\nThe four main NoSQL families:\n\n- **Document** (MongoDB, Couchbase) — JSON-like documents, flexible nested structure.\n- **Key-value** (Redis, DynamoDB, etcd) — simple `key -> value`, extremely fast.\n- **Wide-column** (Cassandra, HBase, ScyllaDB) — rows can have very different columns; great for time-series and high-write workloads.\n- **Graph** (Neo4j, JanusGraph) — nodes and edges, optimised for relationship traversals.\n\nModern systems often mix both — a \"polyglot persistence\" approach with Postgres for transactional data, Redis for caching, Elasticsearch for search, and a wide-column store for telemetry."
