    "question": "How is sharding different from partitioning?",
    "answer": "The two terms are closely related and often used interchangeably, but there's a useful distinction:\n\n- **Partitioning** is the general concept of splitting a dataset into smaller pieces. It can happen within a single database instance (e.g. PostgreSQL table partitioning) or across many.\n- **Sharding** is specifically *horizontal* partitioning *across multiple machines*. Each shard is an independent database instance, usually on its own host.\n\nTwo flavours of partitioning to keep separate:\n\n- **Horizontal partitioning** — split by rows. Rows 1-1M go to one partition, 1M-2M to another. Same schema on each. Sharding is horizontal partitioning across servers.\n- **Vertical partitioning** — split by columns. Hot, frequently-read columns in one table; rarely-accessed BLOBs in another. Same primary key on each.\n\n| Aspect | Partitioning | Sharding |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Scope | Within one DB instance, or across many | Always across multiple DB instances |\n| Primary goal | Manageability, query performance | Scale beyond a single machine |\n| Cross-partition queries | Handled by the DB engine | Application or middleware must coordinate |\n| Operational complexity | Lower | Higher (separate backups, migrations, monitoring) |\n| Failure isolation | Limited — one DB instance | Strong — one shard failing leaves others available |\n\nA practical rule of thumb: reach for partitioning first (it's much cheaper operationally), and only shard when a single beefy database can no longer keep up with writes or storage."
