    "number": 8,
    "question": "How are performance and scalability related?",
    "answer": "They sound similar but describe different properties.\n\n- **Performance** is how fast the system handles a *single* unit of work — low latency, high single-request throughput. A performance problem makes the system slow even for one user.\n- **Scalability** is how well performance holds up as load (or data) grows. A scalability problem means the system is snappy for one user but degrades sharply under concurrent load.\n\nA formal definition: a system is **scalable** if adding resources produces a proportional increase in capacity. Two ways to scale:\n\n- **Scale up** (vertical) — bigger machine.\n- **Scale out** (horizontal) — more machines.\n\nYou can have one without the other:\n\n- A tightly-written single-threaded service can be very fast for one request (great performance) but completely unable to use a second CPU core (zero scalability).\n- A distributed system can scale to thousands of nodes (great scalability) while each individual request is slow because of coordination overhead (poor performance).\n\nIn practice the goals interact:\n\n- Fixing a performance problem (caching, better algorithms, denormalisation) often makes scaling cheaper because each node can do more work.\n- Scaling out introduces network hops, which hurts single-request latency — so there's usually a tradeoff between the two.\n\nAmdahl's Law and the Universal Scalability Law (USL) are the standard quantitative tools: USL in particular shows that contention and coherency costs eventually cause throughput to *decrease* as you add nodes."
