    "number": 9,
    "question": "What is caching, and what are the common cache update strategies?",
    "answer": "**Caching** stores copies of frequently-accessed data in a fast layer (memory, SSD, or a CDN edge) so subsequent requests don't have to recompute or refetch from the slow source of truth. It is the single most effective lever for improving read latency and reducing load on databases.\n\nCaches show up at every layer: CPU caches, OS page cache, browser cache, CDN edge cache, application in-memory cache, and distributed caches like Redis or Memcached.\n\nThe four classic write strategies:\n\n- **Cache-aside (lazy loading)** — the application looks in the cache first; on a miss, it reads from the database and populates the cache. Writes go directly to the database, optionally invalidating the cache entry. Simple and resilient (a cache failure doesn't break writes), but the first read after a miss is slow, and stale data is possible if you forget to invalidate. Memcached and Redis are typically used this way.\n- **Write-through** — writes go to the cache, which synchronously writes to the database before acknowledging. The cache is always consistent with the database, and subsequent reads are fast. Writes are slower, and items written but never read still occupy cache.\n- **Write-behind (write-back)** — writes go to the cache and return immediately; the cache asynchronously flushes to the database. Very fast writes and good batching, but risk of data loss if the cache dies before flushing.\n- **Refresh-ahead** — the cache proactively refreshes entries that are about to expire and are likely to be requested again. Reduces tail latency for hot keys, wasted work for cold ones.\n\nEviction policies (when the cache is full): **LRU** (least recently used) is the default; **LFU** (least frequently used), **FIFO**, and **TTL**-based eviction are also common. **TinyLFU** and **ARC** are smarter modern alternatives used by Caffeine and others.\n\nWatch out for: cache stampedes (many clients refetching at once after an expiry — fix with request coalescing or a \"lock + refresh\" pattern), thundering herds, and cache invalidation bugs (the proverbial \"two hard things in computer science\")."
