    "number": 10,
    "question": "What consistency patterns are available in system design?",
    "answer": "**Consistency** in this context (different from the C in ACID) is about *how soon* a read will see a previous write when data is replicated across multiple nodes. The main patterns, from weakest to strongest:\n\n- **Weak consistency** — after a write, reads may or may not see the new value. There are no guarantees about ordering or when the value will become visible. Good for use cases where stale data is harmless and latency is critical: VoIP, live video, multiplayer games (you don't want to replay frames that already passed).\n- **Eventual consistency** — after a write, reads will *eventually* return the latest value, usually within milliseconds. Data is replicated asynchronously. Used widely in highly-available systems: DNS, email, Cassandra, DynamoDB, S3. Variants include **read-your-writes**, **monotonic reads**, and **causal consistency**, which add useful guarantees without paying the full cost of strong consistency.\n- **Strong consistency** — after a write completes, every subsequent read sees that write (or a newer one). Achieved with synchronous replication and consensus protocols. Used by RDBMS, file systems, Spanner, etcd, ZooKeeper. Necessary for transactions and anywhere correctness depends on serial ordering.\n\nClosely-related stronger guarantees:\n\n- **Linearizability** — operations appear to happen instantaneously at some point between their invocation and response, and respect real-time ordering. The strongest single-object guarantee.\n- **Serializability** — concurrent transactions produce the same result as *some* serial order of those transactions. The strongest multi-object guarantee.\n- **Strict serializability** = linearizability + serializability. Spanner aims for this globally.\n\nChoosing the right pattern is about matching guarantees to the business need. Strong consistency costs latency and availability (per CAP); weak consistency makes correctness reasoning the application's problem. Tunable consistency (Cassandra's `ONE`/`QUORUM`/`ALL`, DynamoDB's strongly-consistent reads) lets you pick per-operation."
