    "question": "What is a content delivery network (CDN)?",
    "answer": "A **CDN** is a geographically distributed network of edge servers that cache and serve content from a location physically close to the end user. The goal is to shorten round-trip time, reduce origin server load, and absorb traffic spikes.\n\nWhat CDNs typically serve:\n\n- **Static assets** — images, video, CSS, JavaScript, fonts, downloadable files.\n- **Streaming media** — HLS/DASH segments for live and on-demand video.\n- **Dynamic content** — increasingly, with edge compute and request collapsing.\n- **API responses** — with cache headers and tag-based invalidation.\n\nTwo delivery models:\n\n- **Push CDN** — you actively upload (push) content to the CDN whenever it changes. Storage at the edge is always up-to-date; good for small, infrequently-changing catalogs and low-traffic sites.\n- **Pull CDN** — the CDN fetches from the origin on the first request, then serves from cache until the TTL expires. The first request to each edge is slower (cache miss), but no upload coordination is needed. Most modern CDNs (Cloudflare, Fastly, CloudFront, Akamai) default to this model.\n\nBenefits:\n\n- **Lower latency** — content served from a POP a few ms away beats a transatlantic round trip.\n- **Lower origin load** — most traffic never reaches your servers.\n- **DDoS absorption** — CDNs have enormous edge capacity and built-in WAF features.\n- **TLS termination at the edge** with modern protocols (HTTP/2, HTTP/3, QUIC).\n- **Global resilience** — outages in one region don't take down the rest.\n\nModern CDNs also offer **edge compute** (Cloudflare Workers, Fastly Compute@Edge, Lambda@Edge) for running logic close to users, and **image / video optimisation**, **request collapsing**, **stale-while-revalidate**, and **tag-based purging** as standard features."
