    "number": 12,
    "question": "What is leader election?",
    "answer": "**Leader election** is the process by which a distributed system designates one node from a group as the **leader** (or primary, master, coordinator) responsible for a specific role — for example, accepting writes, scheduling tasks, or coordinating updates to a shared resource. All other nodes act as **followers**.\n\nWhy it's needed:\n\n- Some operations must happen exactly once or in a single serial order (e.g. assigning IDs, advancing a state machine, writing to an external API that doesn't tolerate concurrent updates).\n- It simplifies coordination — followers just listen to the leader instead of negotiating with each other.\n\nWhat a good leader election protocol guarantees:\n\n- **Safety** — at most one leader at any moment (\"no split brain\"). Achieved via quorum: a node can only become leader if a majority of the cluster agrees.\n- **Liveness** — eventually some node becomes leader, even after failures.\n- **Failure detection** — followers detect when the leader is unreachable (usually via heartbeats / lease expiry) and trigger a new election.\n\nThe dominant algorithms today are consensus protocols:\n\n- **Raft** — designed to be understandable; used by etcd, Consul, CockroachDB, TiKV, MongoDB (modified).\n- **Paxos** / **Multi-Paxos** — the original; used by Chubby, Spanner.\n- **ZAB** — used by ZooKeeper.\n\nIn practice most teams don't build leader election from scratch — they delegate it to a coordination service like ZooKeeper, etcd, or Consul, or rely on a managed system that handles it internally (Kafka controller election, Kubernetes leader-elect, Redis Sentinel, etc.)."
