    "answer": "There is no single right answer — the person quizzing you is looking at *how* you think, not whether you produce one specific architecture. A reasonable framework:\n\n1. **Clarify the requirements.** Don't start designing immediately. Ask about:\n   - **Functional requirements** — what features must the system support? What's in scope vs out?\n   - **Non-functional requirements** — expected QPS, data volume, read/write ratio, latency targets, consistency requirements, geographic distribution.\n   - **Constraints** — budget, existing infrastructure, team size.\n2. **Do back-of-the-envelope estimates.** Daily active users, requests per second, storage per year, bandwidth. This grounds every later decision and surfaces bottlenecks early.\n3. **Define the API.** A short list of the main endpoints (or RPC methods, or events) forces clarity about what the system actually does.\n4. **Sketch a high-level design.** Draw the major components: clients, load balancer, application servers, caches, databases, queues, workers, third-party services. Show data flow for the most important operations.\n5. **Dive deep where it matters.** Pick the components most likely to be the hardest or most interesting — usually the data model, the bottleneck path, or whatever the person quizzing you steers toward. Discuss schema, sharding strategy, indexing, caching layers, async vs sync flows.\n6. **Address scale, reliability, and operations.** How does the design handle 10x traffic? What's the failure mode if a component dies? How do you deploy, monitor, and roll back? What does the on-call story look like?\n7. **Acknowledge tradeoffs explicitly.** Every choice has costs: strong vs eventual consistency, SQL vs NoSQL, sync vs async, monolith vs microservices. Calling these out — and explaining why your choice fits the requirements — is more important than picking the \"right\" answer.\n\nThe biggest mistakes to avoid: jumping straight into implementation without requirements, name-dropping technologies without justification, ignoring failure modes, and forgetting to do the math."
