    "number": 14,
    "question": "What are some of the design issues in distributed systems?",
    "answer": "Distributed systems have to deal with a list of problems that simply don't exist in a single-process program. The classic challenges:\n\n- **Network unreliability** — messages can be lost, delayed, reordered, or duplicated. The network is *not* a reliable, low-latency, infinite-bandwidth pipe (the \"fallacies of distributed computing\").\n- **Partial failure** — some components fail while others keep working. The system has to detect, isolate, and recover from these without manual intervention. Distinguishing \"node is slow\" from \"node is dead\" is fundamentally hard.\n- **No global clock** — nodes' clocks drift, so you can't trust timestamps for ordering events across machines. Logical clocks (Lamport, vector clocks) or hybrid clocks (HLC, TrueTime) are needed.\n- **Consistency vs availability** — the CAP and PACELC tradeoffs force explicit choices about what to give up during partitions and what latency cost you'll pay for stronger consistency.\n- **Concurrency and coordination** — multiple nodes updating shared state need leader election, distributed locking, consensus, or CRDTs. All of these are subtle and easy to get wrong.\n- **Scalability** — performance has to hold up as nodes, users, and data grow. Hot spots, contention, and coordination overhead can cause throughput to collapse (Universal Scalability Law).\n- **Heterogeneity** — different hardware, OS versions, network conditions, and even data centres. Protocols and APIs (gRPC, HTTP/JSON, Protobuf) abstract this, but operational quirks leak through.\n- **Security** — every network hop is a potential attack surface. mTLS, authentication, authorisation, encryption at rest and in transit, and zero-trust architectures are now baseline expectations.\n- **Observability and debugging** — a single user request may touch dozens of services. Without distributed tracing (OpenTelemetry, Jaeger), structured logs, and good metrics, root-causing a failure is nearly impossible.\n- **Deployment, upgrades, and schema evolution** — you can't take everything down at once. Rolling deploys, backwards-compatible APIs, and online schema migrations have to be designed in.\n- **Cost and resource management** — distributed systems waste money easily; right-sizing, autoscaling, and multi-tenancy are real engineering problems.\n\nMost of these reduce to the same root cause: **the system can no longer be reasoned about as a single state machine**, so every design has to account for partial, concurrent, and out-of-order reality."
