    "answer": "**Requirements**\n\n- One-to-one and group chat (group sizes up to a few hundred).\n- Messages persisted server-side for history and multi-device sync.\n- End-to-end encryption.\n- Delivery receipts (sent, delivered, read) and typing indicators.\n- Push notifications when the user is offline.\n- Support for billions of users at thousands of messages per second.\n\n**High-level architecture**\n\n- **Long-lived connections** — clients hold an authenticated WebSocket (or MQTT, as WhatsApp uses) to a connection / gateway tier. This is what makes chat feel instant: no polling, server can push.\n- **Connection tier** is stateless beyond the live socket. A **session registry** (Redis) maps `user_id -> gateway_node` so any message destined for a user can be routed to the gateway holding that socket.\n- **Message service** receives a send, persists the message, fans it out to recipients, and triggers push notifications for offline users.\n- **Message store** — a wide-column store like Cassandra is a classic choice: partition by `conversation_id`, cluster by timestamp descending, so loading the most recent N messages of a chat is a single range read.\n- **Group fanout** — for group chats, the message service writes one copy per recipient inbox (write fanout) so reads are cheap. Very large groups can use read fanout (recipients query the group's message stream) to bound write amplification.\n- **Push notifications** delegated to APNs and FCM.\n\n**Key design choices**\n\n- **Sequence numbers per conversation** — monotonically increasing per chat so clients can detect gaps and resync.\n- **Idempotent send** — clients attach a `client_msg_id` so retries don't duplicate.\n- **Offline queue** — if a recipient is disconnected, the message lives in their inbox and is delivered when their next WebSocket connects.\n- **End-to-end encryption** — the Signal Protocol (X3DH + Double Ratchet) is the standard. The server only sees ciphertext; even metadata can be minimised with sealed sender.\n- **Multi-device sync** — each device gets its own key bundle; sender encrypts to each recipient device individually.\n\n**Scale considerations**\n\n- Connection tier sharded by user; needs sticky routing.\n- Heavy use of regional data centres so latency is low; cross-region replication for the message store.\n- Backpressure and rate limits to handle viral broadcast events."
