    "number": 19,
    "question": "Design a parking lot system.",
    "answer": "**Requirements (functional)**\n\n- Multiple levels, each with multiple rows of spots.\n- Spots come in different sizes: motorcycle, compact, large (for buses/trucks).\n- Vehicles are assigned to the smallest spot that fits.\n- Track availability per level and per spot type.\n- Issue and validate parking tickets.\n- Time-based pricing, supporting different rates by spot type or time of day.\n- Handle entry and exit gates.\n\n**Requirements (non-functional)**\n\n- Concurrency: many gates and many vehicles can enter or leave simultaneously.\n- Reliability: spots must never be double-booked.\n- Auditability: every transaction logged.\n\n**Domain model**\n\n- `ParkingLot` — top-level singleton; owns levels, rates, and overall capacity.\n- `Level` — a floor; owns rows and spots; tracks free counts per spot type for quick availability checks.\n- `ParkingSpot` (abstract) → `MotorcycleSpot`, `CompactSpot`, `LargeSpot`. Each knows whether it can fit a given vehicle.\n- `Vehicle` (abstract) → `Motorcycle`, `Car`, `Bus`/`Truck`. Each declares its required spot size.\n- `Ticket` — issued at entry; contains spot, entry time, vehicle plate.\n- `RateCard` — pluggable pricing strategy (per-hour, tiered, time-of-day).\n- `PaymentProcessor` — handles cash / card / mobile.\n- `EntryGate` / `ExitGate` — orchestrate the workflow.\n\n**Core algorithms**\n\n- **Spot assignment** — pick the smallest free spot that fits the vehicle's class. A larger vehicle may occupy multiple adjacent motorcycle spots if explicitly allowed; otherwise it requires a single sufficient spot. Within a level, prefer closest to entry for user convenience.\n- **Concurrency control** — assigning a spot must be atomic. Either an in-memory lock (single-process) or a row-level lock / conditional update in the database (distributed). Per-level free counters short-circuit a full scan when a level is full.\n\n**Workflow**\n\n1. Vehicle arrives at entry gate → gate scans plate, queries availability.\n2. If full at the requested type, deny entry; otherwise allocate the spot, issue ticket, raise barrier.\n3. On exit, scan ticket → compute fee from entry time and rate card → process payment → release the spot → raise barrier.\n\n**Edge cases worth calling out**\n\n- Lost ticket → flat penalty or full-day rate.\n- Lot full → display dynamic signage, redirect.\n- Power failure → fail-open or fail-closed policy must be deliberate.\n- Reserved spots (EV charging, disabled, monthly) — modelled as spot attributes that filter the pool."
