    "number": 27,
    "question": "Design a web crawler.",
    "answer": "**Requirements**\n\n- Fetch billions of web pages, extract links, and recursively follow them.\n- Respect `robots.txt`, crawl-delay directives, and politeness (don't hammer one host).\n- Detect duplicate pages and avoid re-crawling.\n- Refresh frequently-changing pages more often than static ones.\n- Be resumable, fault-tolerant, and horizontally scalable.\n\n**High-level architecture**\n\n1. **URL Frontier** — the priority queue of URLs to fetch. Sharded by host so politeness is enforced per-host. Internally, often a set of per-host FIFOs plus a global priority queue that picks which host to serve next.\n2. **Fetcher workers** — pull URLs from the frontier, do DNS resolution (cached), establish HTTP connections (keep-alive), download pages with timeouts and size limits, respect `robots.txt` (cached per host).\n3. **Content processor** — parse HTML, extract links, detect content type, run language detection, optionally render JavaScript (headless Chromium) for SPAs.\n4. **De-duplication** — content hash (e.g. SimHash for near-duplicates) checked against a global store. Skip if seen recently.\n5. **URL filter** — normalise (lowercase host, strip fragments, sort query params), check against the seen-URLs Bloom filter, drop unwanted schemes/paths.\n6. **Storage** — pages written to object storage (S3) in WARC format; extracted metadata to a wide-column store (HBase / Cassandra) keyed by URL; link graph to a graph store.\n7. **Scheduler** — feeds newly-discovered URLs back into the frontier with a priority based on PageRank, freshness needs, and source quality.\n\n**Politeness**\n\n- One in-flight request per host at a time by default.\n- Honour `Crawl-Delay` in `robots.txt`.\n- Identify with a real `User-Agent` and a contact URL.\n- Back off on 429 / 5xx.\n\n**Scale**\n\n- Stateless fetchers scale horizontally; frontier shards by host so each shard owns a partition of hosts and its queue.\n- DNS is a real bottleneck — run a local recursive resolver with a large cache.\n- Bloom filter (or counting Bloom filter / cuckoo filter) for the \"seen URLs\" set keeps memory bounded; periodic compaction into a persistent store.\n\n**Freshness**\n\n- Schedule re-crawls per URL based on observed change rate (adaptive interval — pages that change often get crawled often, static pages rarely).\n- Sitemaps and feeds (Atom/RSS) give cheap change signals.\n\n**Crawling vs scraping**\n\n- *Crawling* discovers and downloads pages broadly across many sites.\n- *Scraping* extracts specific structured data from known pages.\nA crawler usually feeds a scraper; legal and ethical constraints differ for each."
