    "number": 29,
    "question": "Design a ride-sharing system like Uber, Lyft, or Ola.",
    "answer": "**Requirements**\n\n- Riders request a ride from current location to a destination.\n- Match rider with a nearby available driver in seconds.\n- Real-time location tracking for both parties.\n- Accurate ETA for pickup and trip.\n- Fare estimation, surge pricing, in-app payment.\n- Trip history, ratings, support.\n- Scale: millions of drivers and riders concurrently across cities worldwide.\n\n**High-level architecture**\n\n- **Mobile clients** (rider, driver) — long-lived connections (WebSocket / gRPC bidi) for low-latency updates.\n- **Edge / API gateway** — auth, rate limiting, request routing to the right region.\n- **Geo / dispatch service** — the hardest piece. Maintains the live location of every available driver and matches them to incoming ride requests.\n- **Trip service** — owns trip state (requested, matched, en-route, in-progress, completed, cancelled).\n- **Pricing service** — base fare + distance + time + surge multiplier.\n- **Payment service** — tokenised payment methods, processed via a gateway (Stripe/Adyen/etc.).\n- **Map / routing service** — usually a third party (Google Maps, Mapbox) or in-house (Uber's own map stack) for ETA and turn-by-turn.\n- **Notification service** — push + SMS for status changes.\n- **Streaming pipeline** — Kafka for location pings, trip events, telemetry feeding analytics, fraud detection, and ML training.\n\n**The hard problem: matching nearby drivers fast**\n\nDrivers send location pings every few seconds. A naive \"scan all drivers within X km\" doesn't scale to millions of drivers. The standard solutions:\n\n- **Geohashing** — encode each lat/long as a short string where shared prefixes mean spatial proximity. Index drivers by current geohash; look up by the rider's geohash prefix (with neighbours).\n- **Quadtrees / R-trees** — spatial trees in memory; classic computational-geometry choice.\n- **Uber's H3** — hexagonal hierarchical grid that has uniform neighbour distances (a real weakness of geohashes). Each city is a sharded H3 index in memory; driver pings update the cell; rider requests query the cell + ring of neighbours.\n\nGeo data is sharded by city / region — there's no reason a New York request needs to see San Francisco drivers, so this shards naturally.\n\n**Storage**\n\n- Trip records in a relational DB sharded by `trip_id` or `region`.\n- Live driver locations in an in-memory store (Redis, or a custom geo service); long-term ping history in a wide-column store (Cassandra).\n- Riders / drivers / vehicles in a relational DB with caches in front.\n\n**Surge pricing**\n\n- Per-region supply/demand monitor — `surge_multiplier = f(active_requests / available_drivers)`.\n- Re-priced every few minutes per zone, displayed to the rider before they confirm.\n\n**ETA**\n\n- Routing service computes a route and returns expected travel time.\n- Continuously corrected from live traffic data and historical patterns; ML model adjusts for known biases (e.g. pickup time at airports).\n\n**Reliability**\n\n- Region-scoped failure domains so a single city's outage doesn't take down the platform.\n- Driver pings are best-effort — losing one is fine, but the matching service needs to detect \"driver hasn't pinged in 30s\" and mark them unavailable.\n- All write paths idempotent; payment in particular needs strong exactly-once semantics."
